<h3>The Question</h3>
<p>
    Change tracking lives today in exactly one place in this repo — the dirty/pristine model inside the
    <a href="/intents/validation/">Validation Intent</a>, with two DI concerns already named in the
    glossary (<code>customValidation:dirty-check</code> and <code>customValidation:change-detection</code>).
    This research takes the position that change tracking is <strong>not a form concern but a facet of
    observability in general</strong>: the problem of <em>detecting, representing, and attributing a
    mutation to state over time</em>. That problem recurs at every layer — form fields, stores and signals,
    documents, collections, the DOM, network sync — and the field has solved it many incompatible ways.
</p>
<p>
    The goal is <strong>not to mandate one strategy</strong> but to (1) catalog them, (2) name the axes
    that distinguish them, and (3) design a layer that lets one app <strong>configure a preferred strategy
    and interoperate between several at once</strong> — generalizing the existing
    <code>customValidation:change-detection</code> concern under the repo's native-first + registry/adapter
    pattern. Full findings, citations, and confidence tags are in the companion report
    (<code>reports/2026-05-31-change-tracking-observability.md</code>), grounded in an adversarially-verified
    deep-research pass (25 claims, 25 confirmed 3-0).
</p>

<h3>Change Tracking IS Observability</h3>
<p>
    This standard sits in the same constellation as <a href="/projects/webstates/">Web States</a>
    (observable stores and signals), <a href="/projects/webtraces/">Web Traces</a> (execution lineage),
    <a href="/projects/webevents/">Web Events</a> (scoped typed dispatch), and
    <a href="/projects/webanalytics/">Web Analytics</a> (user behavior). Each of those already observes
    <em>some</em> change in its own private way. The gap is a <strong>unified change model</strong> (what
    changed: path, old/new, op), an <strong>attribution model</strong> (who/what caused it), and a
    <strong>cross-layer story</strong> for how one mutation propagates from a store into validation, traces,
    analytics, and events.
</p>

<h3>Taxonomy — the classification axes</h3>
<p>Every strategy below is classified on eight axes; the first four are the ones a canonical change record is derived from.</p>
<table>
    <thead><tr><th>Axis</th><th>Values</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
        <tr><td><strong>Granularity</strong></td><td>whole-object · property/key · nested-path · collection-delta · field-within-value</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Eagerness / timing</strong></td><td>sync-on-mutation · microtask-batched · scheduled (frame) · lazy/pull-on-read · polled</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Representation</strong></td><td>flag · old/new pair · path+op · merge-doc · event/command · CRDT op · structural patch</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Attribution</strong></td><td>none · binary (user/program) · typed-source · full provenance (actor + cause + trace link)</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Reversibility</strong></td><td>none · inverse-patch · event-sourced replay · CRDT-convergent</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Transport</strong></td><td>in-memory · serializable · network-merge-safe · log-shippable</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Soundness / coverage</strong></td><td>complete · partial · sampled</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Cost</strong></td><td>interception overhead · snapshot memory · diff CPU · subscription bookkeeping</td></tr>
    </tbody>
</table>

