<h4>Verified highlights</h4>
<ul>
    <li><strong>Signals</strong> use automatic, dynamic, read-time dependency tracking; computed signals are lazy/pull and memoized; propagation is synchronous and glitch-free via topological sort; tracking is synchronous-only, so reads inside <code>setTimeout</code> are not tracked (the key soundness limit). [TC39 Signals; SolidJS]</li>
    <li><strong>Vue 3</strong> combines Proxy interception for objects with getter/setter accessors for refs (a Proxy cannot wrap a primitive), tracking at property-level granularity. [Vue]</li>
    <li><strong>JSON Patch (RFC 6902)</strong> is the proven serializable path+op spine: six ops (add/remove/replace/move/copy/test), each one <code>op</code> + one <code>path</code>, applied in order — but ops are <em>not self-inverting</em>, so reversibility requires carrying the old value. [RFC 6902; immutable-json-patch]</li>
    <li><strong>Immer / Mutative</strong> emit inverse patches alongside forward patches, giving structural-sharing reversibility for undo/replay (paths are arrays, JSON-Patch-shaped but not strictly RFC 6902). [Immer; Mutative]</li>
    <li><strong>CRDTs</strong> guarantee Strong Eventual Consistency in two styles — state-based (join-semilattice + least-upper-bound merge) and op-based (commutative concurrent ops under causal delivery) — the formal basis for concurrent multi-source merge normalization. [Shapiro et al. 2011]</li>
</ul>

<h3>Canonical Change Record <em>(provisional)</em></h3>
<p>
    🔶 The heterogeneous outputs share a recoverable core. A normalization target lets every strategy map
    into one shape so downstream consumers are strategy-agnostic. <strong>Deliberately under-specified for
    now; to be revised as the contract meets real adapters.</strong>
</p>
<we-code-view><pre><code>interface ChangeRecord {
  path: JsonPointer;     // RFC 6901 — the RFC 6902 spine
  op: 'add' | 'remove' | 'replace' | 'move' | 'copy';
  oldValue?: unknown;    // REQUIRED for self-contained reversibility (RFC ops don't carry it)
  newValue?: unknown;
  source: ChangeSource;  // attribution
  timestamp: number;
  version?: string | number;  // optimistic-concurrency / causal token
}</code></pre></we-code-view>
<p>
    The record is a <em>lossy lingua franca for observation</em>, not a replacement for any strategy's
    native form: Merge-Patch is too coarse to be the spine (no arrays), and CRDT ops need an adapter rather
    than a lossless mapping (their convergence lives in causal metadata, not the record).
</p>

<h3>Attribution Model <em>(provisional)</em></h3>
<p>
    🔶 Attribution — who/what caused a change — is the biggest gap today: no strategy carries it natively
    (CRDT/OT carry only a replica/site id). Proposed: a typed <code>ChangeSource</code> channel —
    <code>user</code> · <code>program</code> · <code>server-sync</code> · <code>replay</code>/<code>undo</code>
    · <code>external</code> — generalizing validation's <code>value-input</code> (user) vs
    <code>baseline-change</code> (program/server) distinction. The source rides on the record so a
    mutation's origin survives into revalidation, a trace span, and an analytics event. It may carry a
    W3C Trace Context <code>traceparent</code> so "what caused this mutation" resolves to the initiating
    span; the CloudEvents envelope is prior art for the attributed-change shape.
</p>

<h3>Interop &amp; Configuration Sketch <em>(provisional — flagged for revision)</em></h3>
<p>🔶 The exact mechanism is intentionally not pinned down in this research stage. The shape that fits this repo:</p>
<ul>
    <li><strong>CustomChangeStrategy</strong> — the one contract every strategy satisfies, producing change records from a tracked target. Native store/signal subscriptions are the zero-config default (native-first).</li>
    <li><strong>CustomChangeStrategyRegistry</strong> — registry + provider; per-scope selection through the injector chain lets two strategies coexist in one app (a form subtree on snapshot-diff, a collaborative doc subtree on a CRDT). Generalizes <code>customValidation:change-detection</code>.</li>
    <li><strong>Bridging</strong> — because every strategy emits the same record, one strategy's output can feed another (signals graph → JSON-Patch stream → CRDT document). The lossy mappings mean bridges are adapters, not identities.</li>
    <li><strong>Ordering / merge</strong> — when concurrent sources mutate the same state, defer to the strongest participating model (CRDT convergence rules, or an explicit version/causal token).</li>
</ul>

<h3>Placement Analysis</h3>
<p>
    <strong>Recommendation: a Protocol owned by <a href="/projects/webstates/">Web States</a>, plus a thin
    Change Tracking Intent — with escalation to a net-new Project held in reserve.</strong>
</p>
<ul>
    <li><strong>Protocol under Web States (favored)</strong> — change tracking is fundamentally observing state mutation; Web States owns the emit point (store/signal subscriptions) and its mission already reads "observability and state management." It owns zero protocols today; this is a natural first.</li>
    <li><strong>Thin Change Tracking Intent</strong> — only if a genuine app-wide UX-preference axis exists (preferred strategy / granularity / eagerness / attribution / reversibility) distinct from the technical contract. Decide in Stage 2.</li>
    <li><strong>Escalate to a new Project</strong> ("Web Observability" / "Web Changes") only if the catalog's breadth proves decisive — MutationObserver (DOM), CRDT/OT (network sync), and trace/analytics linkage suggest a cross-cutting substrate that could attract its own plugs/blocks/registries (the Error-Recovery → Web Reliability precedent). Real, but not yet decisive.</li>
</ul>

